    <main>    <h1>F A K E   P R O D U C T S</h1><br>
    <h3>🧪 Fake Products: An Overview</h3>
    <p><strong>Fake products, also known as counterfeit goods, are imitations or unauthorized copies of real products made to deceive consumers. These items are usually sold under the brand name of a legitimate company without permission.</strong></p>
    <h3>🔍 Types of Fake Products</h3><br>
    <h4>Branded Imitations</h4><br>
<ul>
    <li>Shoes, clothing, or bags labeled as Nike, Adidas, Gucci, etc.</li>
    <li>Looks similar but is of poor quality and sold cheaper.</li>
</ul><br>
<h4>Electronics</h4><br>
<ul><li>Fake mobile chargers, earphones, power banks, batteries.</li>
<li>risky: can damage devices or cause fires</li></ul><br>
<h4>Cosmetics & Health Products</h4><br>
<ul><li>Fake shampoos, perfumes, creams, or medicines.</li>
<li>dangerous: may contain harmful or untested ingredients.</li></ul><br>
<h4>Food & Beverages</h4><br>
<ul><li>Duplicate snacks, bottled water, cold drinks.</li>
<li>Risk of poisoning or foodborne illness.</li></ul><br>
<h4>Automobile Part</h4><br>
<ul><li>Fake engine oils, brake pads, or tires.</li>
<li>Dangerous and can lead to accidents.</li></ul><br>
<h2>🚨 Risks of Using Fake Products</h2>
<table border="1" cellpadding="10" cellspacing="0">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Risk</th>
      <th>Description</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>⚠️ Health Hazards</td>
      <td>Fake medicines and cosmetics can cause serious health issues.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>🔥 Fire Risk</td>
      <td>Counterfeit electronics can overheat or explode.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>💸 Financial Loss</td>
      <td>You lose money on a low-quality, non-guaranteed item.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>❌ No Warranty</td>
      <td>Fake goods offer no replacement or customer support.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>🧑‍⚖️ Legal Issues</td>
      <td>Selling or distributing fakes is illegal and punishable.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table><br>
<h2>🛡️ How to Identify Fake Products</h2><br>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Price too good to be true</strong> — Example: iPhone for ₹2,000</li>
  <li><strong>Poor packaging and spelling errors</strong></li>
  <li><strong>No QR codes or barcodes</strong></li>
  <li><strong>No warranty or bill</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Different logo or slightly altered brand name</strong> — like “Adibas”</li>
</ul><br>
<h2>✅ Tips to Avoid Buying Fakes</h2><br>
<ul>
  <li>Buy from <strong>authorized dealers or official websites</strong>.</li>
  <li>Compare the product with the <strong>original brand's listing</strong>.</li>
  <li>Check <strong>reviews</strong>, <strong>ratings</strong>, and <strong>seller credibility</strong>.</li>
  <li>Look for <strong>certifications, barcodes, holograms</strong>, and <strong>authenticity seals</strong>.</li>
</ul>
